nsprüchen.  aThis book provides an updated approach to the immanent criticism in our time. Every kind of criticism - from Hegel to the Frankfurt School - is addressed using this term, which criticizes its object out of its own normative principles and without reference to other measures.The contributions show how the immanent critique in various fields (philosophy, sociology, media theory, and social criticism) analyzes issues and questions them in convincing ways - beginning with its own Geltung standards and truth standards.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn German.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aImmanence (Philosophy)vCongresses. 0aImmanence (Philosophy)zGermany. 0aSocial sciencesxPhilosophyvCongresses. 0aSocial sciencesxPhilosophy. 4aDeutsche Philosophiegeschichte. 4aKritische Theorie. 4aNormativität. 4aPhilosophie. 4aSozialität. 4aSozialphilosophie. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Social.2bisacsh  aGerman History of Philosophy.  aPhilosophy.  aSocial Philosophy.  aSocial Relations.1 aHeins, Volker M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHerzog, Benno, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKozlarek, Oliver, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaiso, Jordi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRomero, José M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRomero, José M., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSalonia, Michele, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStahl, Titus, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVoirol, Ouvier, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZamora, José A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package